The most important finding was the manner in which the electrons in a metal on the so called fermi surface, influence and control the magnetic structure of the material. We investigated this using a combination of experiments at large scale scientific facilities in the United Kingdom and Japan, and state of the art computational methods</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Our research findings are of general interest to others in the field of condensed matter physics notably in the field of quantum magnetism and frustrated magnetism. At the higher level our research gives new understanding in physics that may be of use in the field of electronics, specifically spintronics.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>4CAADC14-F6A0-44C4-80B2-0F94C36C61C4</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Electronics,Energy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/5C72B3E3-C7E6-4B66-9FD2-90027F84B20E"><gtr:id>5C72B3E3-C7E6-4B66-9FD2-90027F84B20E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Determination of spin and orbital magnetization in the ferromagnetic superconductor UCoGe</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Physical Review B</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/e1fed3b9e224128dc624fc6032930c4a"><gtr:id>e1fed3b9e224128dc624fc6032930c4a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Butchers M</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/8D5B4DDF-FF8A-46C2-8CD2-A543C13D58EE"><gtr:id>8D5B4DDF-FF8A-46C2-8CD2-A543C13D58EE</gtr:id><gtr:title>Magnetic frustration, short-range correlations and the role of the paramagnetic Fermi surface of PdCrO2.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationT